    "name": "Hardedge",
    "profile": "[b]Hardedge[/b] [a=Velibor Pedevski], is a sound designer based in New York. His experimental approach to sound, space, and structure is inspired and based on the fundamental principles of the Chicago's [i]A.A.C.M.[/i] creative thinkers, especially their revolutionary multi-directional, non-progressive approach, and the use of silence as a musical element.\r\n\r\nFor many years, Pedevski had been extensively collaborating with many significant members of the A.A.C.M. (mostly as their representative), including [a=Muhal Richard Abrams], [a=Anthony Braxton], [a=Henry Threadgill], [a=Wadada Leo Smith], [a=Roscoe Mitchell], [a=Leroy Jenkins], [a=The Art Ensemble Of Chicago], and [a=George Lewis]. In 1996, he became a co-founder of [l=Braxton House] label, and produced several albums by [a=Anthony Braxton] on it, such as [r=3324472], [r=3325294], [r=1203212], [r=1203222], [r=2210175], and [r=3325194]. From 1993 to 2006, Velibor Pedevski had been teaching the music of Cecil Taylor, Albert Ayler,",
